# .privacy-allow — declare intentionally-synthetic data so the guard stops
# flagging it. COMMIT this file (unlike .privacy-patterns, which is per-clone
# and gitignored). Demo-data location is a property of the repo, the same for
# every clone, so it's versioned with the repo and reviewable in a diff.
#
# Why this exists: realistic demo data is realistic ON PURPOSE — a sample LAN
# IP, a fake MAC, a seed CSV of asset serials. A regex cannot tell those from
# a real leak, and good fixtures will always look like the thing they imitate.
# So the tool does not guess; the repo declares. Burden moves from "the
# scanner infers intent" (impossible) to "you mark the path once" (trivial).
#
# Format: one git path-glob per line. `#` comments and blank lines ignored.
# Globs use git's :(glob) magic — write the `**` explicitly:
#
#   public/samples/**          # whole directory subtree
#   src/lib/seed/**
#   prisma/seed.ts             # a single file
#   tests/fixtures/**
#   **/*.demo.csv              # by extension, anywhere in the tree
#
# Scope tightly. Excluding `tests/**` wholesale also blinds the guard to a
# real secret accidentally pasted into a test — prefer the narrowest path that
# covers the fixture (e.g. tests/fixtures/** over tests/**).
#
# This file feeds the BASH pattern layer (RFC1918 IPs, MACs, /home/<user>/
# paths — the workspace-specific patterns). For a match found by GITLEAKS
# inside demo data instead, add the path to [allowlist].paths in .gitleaks.toml.
